Thomas August Darnell Browder (born August 12, 1950), known professionally as August Darnell and under the stage name Kid Creole, is an American musician, singer and songwriter.
Darnell was born in The Bronx in 1950.
As an adult, Thom Browder began going by his two middle names, August Darnell.
Darnell began his musical career in a band named The In-Laws with his half-brother, Stony Browder Jr., in 1965.
In 1974, again with Stony Browder, he formed Dr. Buzzard's Original Savannah Band, becoming its lyricist and bass player.
The band combined swing and Latin music with disco rhythms and had its biggest hit in 1976 with "Cherchez La Femme".
In 1979, Darnell left Dr. Buzzard's Original Savannah Band.

He also began producing for other artists, such as Don Armando's Second Avenue Rhumba Band and Gichy Dan's Beachwood No.9, before adopting the name Kid Creole (adapted from the Elvis Presley film King Creole) in 1980.
The group released three albums, Off the Coast of Me (1980), Fresh Fruit in Foreign Places (1981) and Tropical Gangsters (1982), that became especially popular and successful in Europe.

Darnell moved to England in the 1980s, and later lived in Denmark, Sweden, and Maui, and occasionally tours Kid Creole and the Coconuts with his European band.

Darnell's daughter Savanna appeared as a contestant on the 2018 series of Love Island, while his son Dario 'Youngr' Darnell appeared as the opening act on the second episode of Simon Cowell's new music competition for ITV called Walk the Line (13 December 2021).
